column6: ['Sports', 'Foreign Policy', 'Non-US Politics']
column11: The Democratic People's Republic of Korea has athletes that could be eligible to participate (Korea Times, Reuters) in the 2018 Winter Olympics hosted by South Korea. However, North Korea has not yet announced whether it will send an athletic delegation to the event (Yonhap News). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

However, as things now stand, they have more to gain in terms of international perception and, most importantly, how they can portray the event domestically.

Broadly, North Korea does make a point of participating in the Olympic Games, though they're significantly more successful/consistent at the Summer versus Winter Games. I’m considering that DPRK will send its pair of figure skaters to compete. Considering equal skating ability, DPRK has a 15% chance of winning a medal. Given that in a given Olympics there are 5-7 pairs that are considered stronger than the others, I’m applying greater coefficients to those pairs, which leaves me at 11% for DPRK. Specifically this pair finished 15th in the 2017 world championships. Even if the DPRK sends more athletes, I expect this pair will be their best chance at winning a medal. Regarding DPRK’s participation: although it seems likely that they will attend the events, I’m concerned they may renege on the agreement given their history of disruption around the Olympic games.
